-- 
Crude Oil Volatility Falls as October Contract Little Changed

-- B y   A a r o n   C l a r k
-- 
2011-08-19T20:56:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-19/crude-oil-volatility-falls-as-october-contract-little-changed.html
Oil options volatility fell as the
underlying futures moved the least in three weeks.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
October, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options prices, was 47.83 percent as of 4 p.m. in  New
York , down from 47.95 percent yesterday.  Crude for October delivery fell 10 cents to $82.41 a barrel
on the  New York Mercantile Exchange , the smallest change since
July 28. The front-month contract has declined 28 percent since
hitting a 2011 high of $113.93 on April 29.  The most active options contract in electronic trading
today was October $70 puts, with 2,870 lots changing hands. They
fell 16 cents to $1.12 a barrel. December $65 puts, the next-
most active option, dropped 9 cents to $1.98 a barrel with 1,593
lots trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of crude.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information on floor trading, where the
bulk of options trading occurs, the next business day.  October $75 puts were the most active options traded
yesterday, with 11,961 lots changing hands. They added $1.46 to
$2.18 a barrel. The next-most active options, October $80 puts,
gained $2.15 to $3.55 on volume of 7,544 lots.  Open interest was highest for December $100 calls with
47,800 contracts. Next were December $120 calls with 43,921 lots
and December $70 puts with 42,390.  To contact the reporter on this story:
